top_5_pain_points:
  1. "Nobody told me what to do after leaving the salon" — First-time setters leave with zero aftercare instruction. They don't know about the 24-hour water rule, cuticle oil, or gloves. The first week is the most vulnerable window and users are going in blind.
  2. "My cuticles look ashy and dry the day after" — A near-universal complaint in nail communities. Users are confused and embarrassed; they expected their nails to look fresh for weeks. Cause is filing, buffing, and chemical exposure during application — not a product failure.
  3. "One nail is lifting at the side — should I peel it off?" — Lifting at the lateral wall (specifically common with almond shape because of side filing) causes genuine anxiety. Users either peel it (causing nail plate damage) or ignore it (risking bacterial infection under the product). Neither is right, and no one has told them this.
  4. "How long do I actually have to wait to shower / do dishes / swim?" — There is genuine confusion about the first 24–48 hour rule. Users either don't know it exists or get conflicting answers. They also don't know *why* — understanding the chemistry (product still curing, bond still forming) would help compliance.
  5. "My nails look dull after 3–4 days — what went wrong?" — Users expect 2–3 weeks of fresh-from-salon shine. The dull look that creeps in from daily hand-washing and hand sanitiser use surprises them. They don't know about top coat refresh or the role of cuticle oil in maintaining gloss.

user_sentiment: Excited but quietly anxious — they've invested money and time and are scared of doing something wrong, but most platforms give them nothing useful after the appointment.

